{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619314"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:31:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:31:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16553"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16553"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.04,0.11,0.67,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9244"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75720"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9244"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16553"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61238"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1708"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6677"},{"type":"tags","id":"7162"},{"type":"tags","id":"11340"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21901"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21904"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75720"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset right-sided weakness and slurred speech. He has a history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His medications include metformin, perindopril and amlodipine. On examination, he is alert and oriented. His observations are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBlood pressure 168/95 mmHg\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPulse rate 82/min\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETemperature 36.7\u00b0C\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERespiratory rate 16/min\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOxygen saturation 98% on room air\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has right-sided hemiparesis affecting his face, arm and leg. Computed tomography of the brain shows a small hypodense region in the left basal ganglia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following arteries most likely supplies the affected brain region?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior choroidal artery","Pericallosal artery","Posterior cerebral artery","Lenticulostriate arteries","Thalamoperforating arteries"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a lacunar stroke affecting the left basal ganglia region, manifesting as right-sided hemiparesis. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elenticulostriate arteries\u003C/strong\u003E are penetrating branches of the middle cerebral artery that supply the basal ganglia, internal capsule, and surrounding white matter. These small vessels are particularly vulnerable to damage from chronic hypertension, making them a common site for lacunar infarcts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior choroidal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies parts of the internal capsule and temporal lobe but is not the primary supply to the basal ganglia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epericallosal artery\u003C/strong\u003E is the continuation of the anterior cerebral artery and supplies the corpus callosum and medial portions of the frontal and parietal lobes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the occipital lobe and inferior temporal lobe\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethalamoperforating arteries\u003C/strong\u003E are branches of the posterior cerebral artery that supply the thalamus\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the vascular anatomy of the brain is crucial for localising strokes and predicting their clinical manifestations. Lacunar infarcts in the territory of the lenticulostriate arteries typically present with pure motor stroke, pure sensory stroke, or sensorimotor stroke, depending on the exact location of the infarct.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The lenticulostriate arteries are penetrating branches of the middle cerebral artery that supply the basal ganglia and internal capsule.","Occlusion of lenticulostriate arteries commonly results in lacunar strokes affecting these deep brain structures.","Understanding cerebral vascular anatomy is crucial for localising strokes and predicting their clinical manifestations."],"references":["Xu X, Wu X, Zhu C, Zhang R, Jiaerken Y, Wang S, Hong H, Yu W, Li K, Zeng Q, Luo X, Yu X, Sun J, Zhang M, Huang P. Characterization of Lenticulostriate Arteries and Its Associations With Vascular Risk Factors in Community-Dwelling Elderly. Front Aging Neurosci. 2021 Jun 22;13:685571. doi: 10.3389/fnagi.2021.685571. PMID: 34239436; PMCID: PMC8258402.","Jiang S, Cao T, Yan Y, Yang T, Yuan Y, Deng Q, Wu T, Sun J, Wu S, Hao ZL, Anderson CS, Wu B. Lenticulostriate artery combined with neuroimaging markers of cerebral small vessel disease differentiate the pathogenesis of recent subcortical infarction. J Cereb Blood Flow Metab. 2021 Aug;41(8):2105-2115. doi: 10.1177/0271678X21992622. Epub 2021 Feb 9. PMID: 33563077; PMCID: PMC8327122.","Navarro-Orozco D, S\u00e1nchez-Manso JC. Neuroanatomy, Middle Cerebral Artery. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526002/","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61238"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16553"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61238"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T20:25:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T20:27:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9244"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75720"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":n